{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17600423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17600423"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:02:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:02:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15613"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15613","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15613"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8304"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62054"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8304","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8304"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15613"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47500"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7009"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20041"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20044"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62054","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62054"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMultiple Endocrine Neoplasia (MEN) syndromes are inherited conditions that affect multiple endocrine glands.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following combinations correctly describes the components of Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia type 2A?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Medullary thyroid carcinoma, phaeochromocytoma, and primary hyperparathyroidism","Parathyroid tumours, pituitary adenoma, and pancreatic tumours","Medullary thyroid carcinoma, phaeochromocytoma, and mucosal neuromas","Parathyroid hyperplasia, pancreatic tumours, and pituitary adenoma","Phaeochromocytoma, paraganglioma, and gastrointestinal stromal tumours"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMultiple Endocrine Neoplasia type 2A (MEN2A) is characterised by the triad of \u003Cstrong\u003Emedullary thyroid carcinoma, phaeochromocytoma, and primary hyperparathyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E. This differs from MEN1 which includes \u003Cstrong\u003Eparathyroid tumours, pituitary adenoma, and pancreatic tumours\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMEN2B includes \u003Cstrong\u003Emedullary thyroid carcinoma, phaeochromocytoma, and mucosal neuromas\u003C/strong\u003E. The combination of \u003Cstrong\u003Eparathyroid hyperplasia, pancreatic tumours, and pituitary adenoma\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as it mixes elements of different syndromes. \u003Cstrong\u003EPhaeochromocytoma, paraganglioma, and gastrointestinal stromal tumours\u003C/strong\u003E represent a different familial syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMEN2A is caused by mutations in the RET proto-oncogene and follows an autosomal dominant inheritance pattern. Nearly all patients develop medullary thyroid carcinoma, while approximately 50% develop phaeochromocytoma, and 20-30% develop primary hyperparathyroidism.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia type 2A (MEN2A) consists of medullary thyroid carcinoma, phaeochromocytoma, and primary hyperparathyroidism.","MEN2A is caused by mutations in the RET proto-oncogene with autosomal dominant inheritance."],"references":["Heinlen JE, Buethe DD, Culkin DJ, Slobodov G. Multiple endocrine neoplasia 2a presenting with pheochromocytoma and pituitary macroadenoma. ISRN Oncol. 2011;2011:732452. doi: 10.5402/2011/732452. Epub 2011 Apr 18. PMID: 22091429; PMCID: PMC3200135.","Ungureanu S, \u015eipitco N, Alexa Z, Gon\u0163a V, Bujac M, Parnov M, Romanenco 